{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500447"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:13:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:13:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1645"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1645"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.67,0.17,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45753"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1645"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30681"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1198"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43088"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43848"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45753"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents complaining of swollen hands and feet for the past 3 months. Over the last 6 months, she reports dysphagia, abdominal bloating and heartburn. She also notes worsening fatigue and joint pain in both hands. Of particular concern to the patient is the new onset of \u0027spider veins\u0027 on her face and hands, which she deemed unsightly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the tips of her fingers appear white, and her hands and feet appear puffy. Serology testing returned highlighting a positive ANA, and ANA immunofluorescence showed a centromere pattern. Pulmonary function tests showed no abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia","Systemic sclerosis","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome","Rheumatoid arthritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E (SSc) is an autoimmune inflammatory condition that often occurs between the ages of 35-55yo and results in thickening and hardening of the skin. It causes diffuse fibrosis and vascular abnormalities that affect the skin, lungs, gastrointestinal tract, heart and the kidneys. Systemic sclerosis is subclassified into diffuse cutaneous or limited cutaneous depending on if skin thickening is distal to the elbows and knees (limited SSc) or extends more proximally (diffuse SSc). The mechanisms of the disease remain largely unknown but as with other autoimmune conditions, is thought to occur from the interaction of environmental and genetic risk factors. Typically, systemic sclerosis presents with sclerodactyly (thickening of the skin on the fingers and toes), abnormal nail fold capillaries, puffy fingers and toes (often seen in early systemic sclerosis, preceding the development of skin thickening), Raynaud\u2019s phenomenon, microstomia (an oral aperture of less than \u0026lt;4.5cm of interlabial distance) and internal organ fibrosis or vascular damage (often involving the lungs, GI system and/or kidneys) often causing reflux, bloating, or other GI, renal, or cardiopulmonary symptoms. To diagnose systemic sclerosis, patient investigations should show sclerodactyly, abnormal nail folds capillaries, and positive ANA (anti-Scl70, anti-centromere or anti-RNA polymerase III antibodies - the three autoantibodies are thought to be mutually exclusive) on serology, and/or internal organ fibrosis and vascular damage. This patient presents with systemic features that are also present in systemic sclerosis (fatigue, bloating, heartburn), as well as specific features including Raynaud\u2019s phenomena, puffy hands and feet, and positive ANA on serology. Therefore, it is likely this patient is presenting with systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune condition that can affect any organ system. Common features include fatigue, fevers, mucositis, rashes (e.g. a malar (\u0027butterfly\u0027) rash that worsens with UV exposure), arthritis, Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, myalgia, serositis (e.g. pleuritic, pericarditis), glomerulonephritis and cytopenias. Similarly to systemic sclerosis, ANA is present in almost all SLE patients. However, SLE rarely results in sclerodactyly and telangiectasia, as in systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia (HHT) \u003C/strong\u003E(or Osler-Rendu-Weber syndrome) is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by endoglin and activin receptor-like kinase type 1 gene mutations on chromosomes 9 and 12 respectively. A mutation in one of these genes leads to abnormal blood vessels being prone to rupture causing telangiectasia, or arteriovenous malformations (AVM) if larger blood vessels are involved. HHT most commonly causes telangiectasias in the nose and recurrent epistaxis, usually beginning during teenage or early adulthood years, both of which are not seen or reported in this patient. Between the ages of 20-40yo, telangiectasias can begin to be seen in the upper half of the body including the face, mouth, lips, ears, conjunctiva, upper limbs, and often most easily seen in the nail beds, all of which are not reported or seen in this patient. Additionally, abnormal blood vessel formation can occur in the GI system causing GI bleeding in 25% of patients and AVM in the lungs of approximately 30% of patients. This patient reports bloating and heartburn which are not known to be associated with HHT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Eis another autoimmune condition that commonly results in xerostomia (dry mouth), dry eyes and arthralgias. It may also manifest with Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon and dysphagia. However, Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome would not account for the patient\u0027s telangiectasia (or \u0027spider veins\u0027), and she would likely complain of dry eyes and/or mouth. Patients with Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome commonly have positive anti-SSA/Ro and anti-SSB/La antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis (RA) \u003C/strong\u003Eis an autoimmune condition that typically manifests as a symmetrical arthritis of the small joints of the hands and feet (sparing the distal interphalangeal joints), wrists, elbows, shoulders, knees and ankles. Stiffness is often marked, persisting for longer than 30 minutes upon waking. Extra-articular manifestations may include: interstitial lung disease, pericarditis, anaemia, Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, rheumatoid nodules and oesophageal dysmotility. However, RA would not account for the patient\u0027s telangiectasia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sclerodactyly, oedematous hands and feet, microstoma, internal organ fibrosis or vascular damage, and a positive ANA (anti-Scl70, anti-centromere and/or anti-RNA polymerase III antibodies) are key to diagnosing systemic sclerosis."],"references":["Ho, Y.Y. et al., 2014. Fibrosis - A lethal component of systemic sclerosis. Nature reviews. Rheumatology, 10(7), pp.390\u2013402.","Denton, Christopher P, Prof \u0026 Khanna, Dinesh, Prof, 2017. Systemic sclerosis. The Lancet (British edition), 390(10103), pp.1685\u20131699.","Ardelean, D.S. \u0026 Letarte, M., 2015. Anti-angiogenic therapeutic strategies in hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia. Frontiers in genetics, 5, p.35.","Kassan SS, Moutsopoulos HM. Clinical manifestations and early diagnosis of Sj\u00f6gren syndrome. Arch Intern Med. 2004 Jun 28;164(12):1275-84. doi: 10.1001/archinte.164.12.1275","Aletaha D, Smolen JS. Diagnosis and Management of Rheumatoid Arthritis: A Review. JAMA. 2018;320(13):1360\u20131372. doi:10.1001/jama.2018.13103","Ringold S, Lynm C, Glass RM. Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. JAMA. 2005;293(24):3130. doi:10.1001/jama.293.24.3130"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30681"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1645"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30681"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-21T12:11:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-21T12:11:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1645"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45753"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links